Class Student

java.lang.Object
fi.tuni.prog3.sisu.Student
All Implemented Interfaces:
java.lang.Comparable<Student>
public class Student
extends java.lang.Object
implements java.lang.Comparable<Student>
Defines a student. Students can take up courses and get attainments for passing them.

    • getAttainmentsPerPeriod

      public double[] getAttainmentsPerPeriod()
      Returns an array of the student's attainments per period in their current degree since they started studying. The first element of the returned array is the credits per period that the student must meet in order to graduate in time.
      Returns:
      The student's attainments per period in their current degree since they started studying + the credits per period that the student must meet in order to graduate in time (first element).

    • updateAttainment

      public java.lang.String updateAttainment​(Course selectedCourse, int grade, java.time.LocalDate completionDate, boolean completed)
      Handles changes to the student's attainments list. No changes are made if any of the parameters aren't valid.
      Parameters:
      selectedCourse - The selected course.
      grade - The grade of the selected course.
      completionDate - The date of the new attainment.
      completed - Boolean value if the course is marked completed or not.
      Returns:
      String of "Attainment removed." or "Attainment updated." or "Attainment created." if everything is ok.
      String of "Invalid grade." if the grade is invalid.
      String of "Date is null." if the date is null.
      String of "Invalid date." if the date is invalid.

    • compareTo

      public int compareTo​(Student other)
      Comparing students is done with student numbers.
      Specified by:
      compareTo in interface java.lang.Comparable<Student>
      Parameters:
      other - The student compared to.
      Returns:
      • 0 if the student numbers are equal.
      • Less than 0 if the student number is lexicographically less than the other's.
      • Greater than 0 if the student number is lexicographically greater than the other's (more characters).
